Mother Earth isn't the only one preparing for a new season. 🌓 As you welcome a baby and transition into motherhood, honor YOUR new season with intentionality, flexibility and grace.✨
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
P.S. Our new season takes root 09.21 at 6 pm PST. Subscribe to our newsletter for an exclusive discount at launch! (Link in AW21 highlight!)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Solly Baby on September 18, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'TAKE TAKEROOT ROOT A New Mother's Guide Guide to Staying Grounded'.

Photo by Solly Baby on September 18, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'AW21 TAKE ROOT Seek out sources of nourishment. Internal: hydration, healthy foods, rest, mediation External: chats with family + friends, warm baths, fresh air 1/7'.

Photo by Solly Baby on September 18, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'AW21 TAKE ROOT Grow confident in your convictions. Trust that you know what's best for you + your baby. Advocate for that as needed. 2/7'.

Photo by Solly Baby on September 18, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'AW21 TAKE ROOT Do the work beneath the surface. Unpack + heal: family history, infertility and/o and loss, traumatic birth experiences, postpartum depression 3/7'.

Photo by Solly Baby on September 18, 2021. May be an image of flower and text that says 'AW21 TAKE ROOT Hold steady through early motherhood's storms. There will be trying minutes and moments and days. Stay the course and rely on your network when you need extra support. Possible storms: postpartum healing, feeding concerns, lack of sleep, quarrels with your partner (see: lack of sleep). 4/7'.

Photo by Solly Baby on September 18, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'AW21 TAKE ROOT Rely Û on tree. Whether it's relatives or colleagues or neighbors or friends who feel like family, map out a support system and call on them often. 5/7'.

Photo by Solly Baby on September 18, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'AW21 TAKE ROOT Find the light. Surround yourself with people, media and influences that support the narrative of motherhood you wish to write. 6/7'.

Photo by Solly Baby on September 18, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'AW21 TAKE ROOT Allow yourself to blossom. You might feel like a different person than you were before or be inclined to try things you didn't previously think you would. Let go of past expectations or constraints and allow yourself to become whatever form of mother you were meant to be. 7/7'.

node.text:
There's never a bad time to have a baby, but is there not something about autumn that feels particularly perfect for welcoming a little one? 👶🏽🍂 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
‘Tis the season to add a sweater that's big enough to envelope you both 🧶, to inhale so deeply you can practically feel the crisp air as it makes its way to your lungs 🌬, to wrap up baby to your chest in a way that's inexplicably cozy + endlessly therapeutic. ☁️
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Fall is a favorite around here, and our AW21 Collection doesn't do a good job of hiding it. JUST FOUR MORE DAYS. 😍

node.text: 👆🏽 An autumn bucket list for the postpartum mom 🍂📝

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Solly Baby on September 11, 2021. May be an image of 2 people, child, people standing and outdoors.

node.text: I watched the 9/11 documentary on Apple+ (watch it - it’s phenomenal❤️) earlier this week and have been thinking about it ever since, but today I woke up thinking of my friend Ellen. I met Ellen at church two years ago and have loved her ever since. She just had her second baby two months ago. Her husband is in the Middle East on his first deployment. Not really the place to be right now. He was deployed shortly after they found out they were pregnant and missed the birth and everything since then. He should’ve been home by now but — with all of the crazy happening there — isn’t. It’s clear every milestone of Hannah’s feels bittersweet because he isn’t there to see it. I’m so amazed by her strength that when I’m with her sometimes it’s hard for me to carry on a normal conversation because everything I have to say feels so trivial. So I keep giving her more wraps. And baked ziti. And a listening ear. But it all feels so insignificant compared to the weight she is carrying. A military friend of a friend of hers is pregnant and now widowed as her husband was just killed in the airport bombing. Ellen asked if she could use the rest of her Solly gift card I’d given her to get a few things for his widow because that baby is still on its way and that mama will need all the extra hands. As if her own hands aren’t full. I brought my kids to the warehouse with me to pack her a box with all the wraps so we can fit and tear up the whole time, especially as I share their stories with our warehouse team — a team of almost all mothers. They cry too. I bring the box to Ellen a few days later as we meet to do a little hike with some kids from church. She is always saying she has to get out of the house every day to keep busy. To distract herself. We talk as we walk up a short but very steep hill with the babe wrapped on her chest and her toddler at her side. She soldiers on up the hill, sweating and smiling and always moving forward. She frequently comments, jokingly but with at least a little bit of judgment, that she’s a “hot mess”… (cont’d below 👇🏽)

node.text: The only way I can get things done in the house with a baby is through this @sollybaby wrap. Jakov is such a clingy babe. He loves to be held and to be kept close to me especially during his awake time. This wrap helps me a lot in calming him down and it puts him to sleep instantly. I don’t mind wearing him in this for hours because the fabric is lightweight, breathable, comfy and the softest I own. I can say that he feels cozy, calm, secure, and safe close to me using this wrap. A calm baby equals a happy and productive mommy, am I right? @sollybaby really lives up to their line — “Happy baby, free hands, full heart”. Thank you @sollybaby for this. 🤍 @izavanessa for #sollystories
